		<table width="100%">
		<tr>
			<td>
				<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="3"><b>    Paladin Walk Through 1-12</b></font>
					<br>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">
					<b><A href="mailto:tavoelker@ev1.net">Nicophorus</a> | 
		            10/5/1999 3:48:49 PM</b></font></p>
		         <a href="guides.asp">
		         <font face="verdana" size="2">Return to guide listing.</font></a>
					
					<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">A Paladin walk through to level 12.  (This assumes you are starting in Freeport).<BR>
<BR>
The obvious stuff has probably been covered a jillion times over.  Find your guild master... kill rats and bats... yada yada yada.  This is true of all classes, but what makes the Paladin unique?<BR>
<BR>
At the beginning: not much (but yet everything).  You are a bit weaker than a warrior and only have Lay of Hands to seperate you (but what a difference that can make).  Get it prgrammed as a hot key and learn how and when to use it.  You get one use of it per day, so think before you LOH.<BR>
<BR>
Paladins are SLOW.  The only thing slower than a human Paladin is an Ogre trying to do math.  Don't bother trying to run away... you will always fail.  So, be brave and fight on.  If the worst may happen, pick a nice spot to die that you can easily (and safely) find again (learn to use /loc).<BR>
<BR>
Paladins function best in teams.  Group up early.  It shouldn't be hard finding a spell caster looking for a tank even at the earliest of levels.  Once in a group, learn to keep track of your whole team (locations, hit points, what's attacking them).  You will eventually be a backup healer, so it pays off to know the total fight.  Also, if things are getting bad sound the retreat and buy time for your party with your life (remember, you weren't going to escape anyway and it's more heroic to be the guy who holds to the end).<BR>
<BR>
I liked the newbie zones of East and West Freeport well to level 3.  At this point you need to adventure elsewhere.  A number of people go straight to East Commons, but I really think that is a mistake.  Go to the perimeter of North Ro (as close to the Freeport Zone as you can be, if you pass the Inn you will soon be dead).  While Armadillo's and Coyote's don't have any loot of real value, they are a safe solo fight and give good XP to level 5.  At this point, learning how to /con is crucial.  Size up your fights and think about the odds.  Blue isn't a guarantted win solo, and White at early levels can easily go bad.  Never attack a yellow unless you have a good team.<BR>
<BR>
About level 4-6 you can start playing in the East Commons.  There are many spots with good game in the commons, but beware trains.  You will find that some very tough (realtively) creatures will wander through almost every portion of this zone.  A simple fight can turn very ugly when a Lion, Lioness, or Young Kodiak drops in on you.  This is the time and place to master your group fighting skills.  Find a team and practice.<BR>
<BR>
At level 6 (or thereabouts) you get the skill bash.  This is to be your only secondary attack, use it.  Get a shield (if you don't have one already).  As a Paladin you will never get kick or dual wield, so don't worry about two handed weapons.  Stay away form the big slow weapons.  I know a ton of damage per hit looks sexy, but you will get far fewer attacks per round then warriors or the odd monk.  Get a fast weapon with a shield and stick to it and bashing.<BR>
<BR>
This brings up every young warriors favorite weapon: the Mino Axe.  While it is NOT the long term weapon of choice for a Paladin (way too slow), it is a good one as soon as you can afford it.  It packs a whallop and is about the same speed as the rusty and tarnished weapons you can find.  Net effect is, you attack as quickly (or even quicker) and do more damage.  Once you get the axe, start saving for a combine sword...<BR>
<BR>
What about armor?  I worked up the tailoring skill early on.  I made patchwork for myself and most of my regular hunting party, so the newbie armor wasn't a big issue to me.  If this isn't your path, I suggest you find an aspiring tailor and work out a trade arrangement (I give back one piece of armor for every three ruined pelts I am brought).<BR>
<BR>
Things are slow in the Paladins life from level 6-9.  You may even begin regretting your choice as you see your Warrior friends kicking and hitting hard, monks throwing special attacks at furious rates, and even the spell casters starting to come into their own.  You however are still a lesser fighter with one heck of a trump card (the LOH).<BR>
<BR>
Hang in there because things change at level 9.  You get your first spells.  You become a minor healer.  Not as efficient as a Cleric, but you really have the ability to make a difference in the close fights and you can get your team rested up quicker.  <BR>
<BR>
I also recommend the Courage spell.  I make a habit of being the guy who gives out the buffs (save your Clerics mana for fights).  My favorite spell is the overlooked &quot;flash of light.&quot;  This is a huge spell that is just not used often.<BR>
<BR>
With this spell you can actually (sometimes) get away from a close fight by blinding your opponent.  My favorite use though is pulling.  Get in the area of a creature you want to fight.  Target it and throw the flash of light.  The monster will likely go charging off blind in some random direction, but (unless kill stealed) they will be back.  Go find a nice defensive spot and wait.  Whack away... Rinse and repeat...  Lots of fun that spell.<BR>
<BR>
The other nice thing now is the ability to truly help others.  I had always made the habit of standing in on close fights and letting the nearby player know I would help if asked.  Now, I can actually throw a heal or two on them and make sure they can win.  Talk about a way to make friends.  Paladins should be played selflessly.  Helping others is what it's all about.<BR>
<BR>
At level 10 buy Dodge.  Your defensive ability goes throught he roof with this skill.  I have never had a problem sololing lions since getting dodge and rarely take (much) damage in fights.  Continue practicing every casting skill you can.  Work on your quests...<BR>
<BR>
I have recommended helping others throughout the body of this walk through.  That goes double for younger Paladins.  They are walking the same tough road you once walked.  Give them assistance.  I had my tail saved a number of times by higher level Paladins and I help others when I can.  I have given simple tasks to 1-3 level Paldins for a trivial (for me) piece of patchwork armor.  Follow that lead, build the brotherhood...<BR>
<BR>
Luck to You Brothers,<BR>
Nicophorus<BR>
Brell Sirilus Server<BR>
<BR>

